As a global population, the demand we have put on ecological resources and services in 2020 has already exceed what the Earth can regenerate this year. Of course, the responability for this is not shared evenly between countries. If the world lived like Aotearoa New Zealand, we would reach our Earth Overshoot Day on 5 May.

Overshoot is possible only by depleting our natural capital. The costs of this global ecological overspending are becoming increasingly evident in the forms of deforestation, soil erosion, biodiversity loss, and the build-up of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.

It is more important than ever that we do everything we can to make sure the planet we pass on can support our kids and grandkids' future.  Our recovery from the global pandemic provides an opportunity to prioritise work to create this better world. üíöüåè

